            <div class="post vcard"><h2>
            <a href="http://www.viget.com/inspire/jquery-plugin-patterns/">A Few jQuery Plugin Patterns</a>            </h2>
                        <div class="inner_post">

<div class="author_pic davery">

<a class="url" href="/about/team/davery" title="Doug Avery"><img alt="Doug Avery" class="photo" src="/images/inspire/author_image_frame.png" width="112" height="105" /></a></div>




            <span class="author">
          <a href="/about/team/davery">
          <span class="fn n">Doug Avery</span>
          </a>, 
    
ON THE TOPIC OF <a href="http://www.viget.com/inspire/category/javascript/">Javascript</a></span>






        <div class="date_comment clearfix">
          <span class="date">
            12/13<br />2010
          </span>
        <span class="comments"><a href="http://www.viget.com/inspire/jquery-plugin-patterns/#comment_list" title="Leave A Comment">4</a></span></div><!-- date_comment -->



                                                         
                                <p>One of jQuery&rsquo;s great strengths is its simple and powerful plugin architecture. The extensible .fn method has been one key to jQuery&rsquo;s success, it lets developers of any experience level quickly produce and distribute their work, and a lot of devs who work with jQuery use plugins and their patterns every day.</p>

<p>Plugins don&rsquo;t have many hard rules, so it shouldn&rsquo;t surprise anyone to find out that there&rsquo;s a huge diversity in implementation styles. Still, if you look at enough plugins, a few patterns useful patterns emerge.</p>

<p>Here are five patterns, each with their own pros and cons, applied to a simple gallery behavior. If you&rsquo;re already using some of these (or prefer even better ones), let me know in the comments. A few points about all five patterns: I&rsquo;m wrapping the plugin code in an immediate (or &lsquo;self-executing&rsquo;) function to create a closure and assign the $ to jQuery. I&rsquo;m also setting options the standard way, combining a passed-in object with a set of defaults. You play around with the gallery I&rsquo;m trying to make <a href="http://www.viget.com/uploads/file/jQueryPatterns/markup/">here.</a></p>

                                                                            <p><strong><a href="/inspire/jquery-plugin-patterns#continue">Continue reading "A Few jQuery Plugin Patterns"</a></strong></p>                           
                                                   
<p><a href="http://www.viget.com/inspire/jquery-plugin-patterns/">Leave a comment ( 4  )</a></p>

